Class Interval<T extends java.lang.Comparable<T>>

  • java.lang.Object
    • Interval<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - the template parameter for the data field - interval.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    IntervalADT<T>, java.lang.Comparable<IntervalADT<T>>

    public class Interval<T extends java.lang.Comparable<T>>
extends java.lang.Object
implements IntervalADT<T>
    This class defines the Interval for the IntervalNode. This object has three main components: 1) start time of type T 2) end time of type T 3) a label or name represented with a String. This class is used to construct each IntervalNode and will be used to structure the IntervalTree.

        public boolean overlaps(IntervalADT<T> other)
        Description copied from interface: IntervalADT
        Return true if this interval overlaps with the other interval.

        Note: two intervals [a, b], [c, d] will NOT overlap if either b < c or d < a.

        In all other cases, they will overlap.

      • compareTo

        public int compareTo(IntervalADT<T> other)
        Description copied from interface: IntervalADT
        Compares this interval with the other and return a negative value if this interval comes before the "other" interval. Intervals are compared first on their start time. The end time is only considered if the start time is the same.

        For example, if start times are different:

         [0,1] compared to [2,3]: returns -1 because 0 is before 2
 [2,3] compared to [0,1]: return 1 because 2 is after 0
 [0,4] compared to [2,3]: return -1 because 0 is before 2
 [2,3] compared to [0,4]: return 1 because 2 is after 0
 [0,3] compared to [2,4]: return -1 because 0 is before 2
 [2,4] compared to [0,3]: return 1 because 2 is after 0

        If start times are the same, compare based on end time:

         [0,3] compared to [0,4]: return -1 because start is same and 3 is before 4
 [0,4] compared to [0,3]: return 1 because start is same and 4 is after 3

        If start times and end times are same, return 0

        [0,4] compared to [0,4]: return 0
        Specified by:
        compareTo in interface IntervalADT<T extends java.lang.Comparable<T>>
        Specified by:
        compareTo in interface java.lang.Comparable<IntervalADT<T extends java.lang.Comparable<T>>>
        Parameters:
        other - the second interval to which compare this interval with
        Returns:
        negative if this interval's comes before the other interval, positive if this interval comes after the other interval, and 0 if the intervals are the same. See above for details.

      • toString

        public java.lang.String toString()
        Description copied from interface: IntervalADT
        Returns a specific string representation of the interval. It must return the interval in this form.

        For example: If the interval's label is p1 and the start is 24 and the end is 45, then the string returned is:

        p1 [24, 45]
